The warning appears to result from calling `new Buffer(...)` in the transitive dependency `buffer-indexof-polyfill` brought in by `unzipper`.

Sadly, npm does not have an easy way to exclude a transitive dependency. Until it gets fixed I developed a hacky workaround by adding the following script in `package.json`:

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "postinstall": "echo // > node_modules/buffer-indexof-polyfill/index.js # delete transitive dependency polyfill causing deprecation warning until exceljs package fixes it, see exceljs #1433"
  }
}
```

This script will run automatically after `npm install` and will simply make the `index.js` of that package a harmless empty comment. This script will work on both bash and Windows shells.
